 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubaramos1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Baramos1</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 116<br> <font color=#333333>(9/28/02 9:39:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=344.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: hahaha</span><hr size=1> Once again, Damage/Mana ratio doesn't tell the whole story.<br>
<br>
A better ratio, and one that is used by developers, is Damage per Mana PER UNIT TIME.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Equivalently, Damage/(Mana*Time).<br>
<br>
Time does factor in, and &quot;being able to cast other spells during recast&quot; doesn't mean a thing.  It's apples and oranges. I've tried to explain this in other threads, to no avail.  Bottom line is that you either compare single spell-to-spell, or if you want to talk about some hypothetical chain-damage test, you can't limit the Mage to one spell, but give him his choice, as well. <br>
<br>
If you do a rigorous mathematical treatment (not in tabular form, but with derived equations) you'll find TIME in the denominator of a damage function.<br>
<br>
What does this mean?  As time goes up - and this includes recast, damage factor goes down, in simplest terms.  Naturally, there are other terms - the equations are not simple ratios and there are several terms in the equations with sums, differences, and products, but the time factor will have major influence.<br>
<br>
I don't understand why this is hard to understand.  <br>
<br>
Perhaps by stretching the analogy to an absurd extreme it can be seen.  Imagine a Chanter spell that does 1000 damage but has a day long recast, and costs 50 mana.  Now imagine a Mage spell that does only 900 damage but still costs 50 mana, but can be cast every second.  <br>
<br>
Which spell is better?  According to the argument made above about Damage/mana the Chanter spell is better. <br>
<br>
Obviously it is not.<br>
<br>
And that's the spell-to-spell comparison. <br>
<br>
The other argument, that keeps incorrectly getting wound up in these analyses that &quot;using other spells during recast&quot; doesn't hold water either, because the Mage also has other tools in his toolbox, such as rains, that he could be casting, and blasting that one second spell during the delay.<br>
<br>
Two separate arguments with the same conclusion.  In each comparison the Mage will come out ahead.<br>
<br>
In some cases, using some combinations of variables, and given the &quot;stepping linear&quot; form of the functions, you can find crossover points.  In very simplest terms, however, there is a linear function of Damage per Mana per Second that is steeper for the Mage than for the Chanter. (And Druid).<br>
<br>
In addition, blithely ignoring every other Mage direct damage capability when making these claims (and rants) about spells, doesn't give fair treatment to the analysis, but tells an extremely lopsided view of the total story.  After all the raving about our wonderful pets, suddenly saying, &quot;Oh, let's ignore the pet for the sake of this argument,&quot; is utterly invalid.  The pet is just another form of a spell, in graphical form.  Just because his name is Jobaber doesn't change that fact.<br>
<br>
You want to be a caster and be all about DPS? <br>
<br>
The Mage is the King.<br>
<br>
Bara <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usolovey.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Solovey</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 141<br> <font color=#333333>(9/28/02 10:04:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=344.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://myweb.ecomplanet.com/COLL8955/mystorage/fireelemental.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: hahaha</span><hr size=1> This is not a rant thread on black steel/Insanity...The point of this is a long term comparison between the two spells. <br>
<br>
The below test is done using Basic Comparisons...The numbers are Averages taken from some board magelos/Myself.<br>
<br>
Both the enchanter and the magician have 3100 mana.<br>
Both the enchanter and the Magician Have C3 Active on them.<br>
Spec/Mod rods were not counted in the comparison as chanters can also specilize in evoc and use mod rods. <br>
<br>
I gave the mages c3 because simply the 5 minute encounter below is a raid comparison and both the mage and the enc should be buffed. I did not however give them Both PoTG because it would have simply inflated the numbers. Both have a standing mana regen of 15 mana per tick.<br>
<br>
This test is done only using standing mana regen...I am doing another one now using med times however due to work I dont have the time to finish it out (it will be much longer). I have a feeling however in the med time ones it will be almost even but the mage might have an edge.<br>
<br>
The below fight is using a 5 minute fight....Many luclin fights run 30 minutes while mana kunark fights run 1 minute...So I chose an &quot;in between&quot; number...Here is the blow by blow.<br>
<br>
Both can cast 11 times before going oom. The mage will take aprox 99 seconds to cast his mana bar while the chanter will take 154 seconds.....OR 17 ticks for the mage/ 26 ticks for the enchanter. During this time the mage will have regened 255 mana the enc will have regened 390.<br>
<br>
1:39 seconds into the fight mage deals 11,000 Dmg 255 mana<br>
2:32 seconds into the fight enc deals 12100 dmg 390 mana<br>
+3 ticks later (18 seconds)<br>
1:57 seconds into the fight Mage 12,000 damage 25 Mana<br>
2:50 seconds into the fight 13,200 damage 160 Mana<br>
+7 ticks later (42 seconds.)<br>
2:39 seconds into the fight mage 12000 damage 130 mana.<br>
3:32 seconds into the fight enc 13200 dmg 265 mana.<br>
+2 ticks later (12 seconds)<br>
2:51 seconds into the fight mage 12000 damage 160 mana<br>
3:44 seconds into the fight enc 14300 damage 20 mana<br>
+9 ticks later (54 seconds)<br>
3:45 seconds into the fight. Mage 13000 Damage 20 mana<br>
4:39 seconds into the fight enc 14300 Damage 155 Mana<br>
<br>
Ech tick + I went through I calculated in cast time+recast time and gave them mana regen for both...I also used the cast time+recast time to write in the next tick shown. After the last point shown neither class will regen enough mana for another nuke. The finale results are.<br>
<br>
Mage DPS Using the pure magic nuke. 43.3 DPS. 13000 dmg.<br>
Enc DPS Using the pure magic nuke. 47.7 DPS 14300 dmg.<br>
<br>
Pretty close...I think when I finally get to do the med times the numbers will be diffrent.<br>
